# Day 15 – Security vs. Compliance: Why Passing the Audit Is Not the Same as Being Safe | 100 Days of GRC
*By Ibrahim Abdullahi | 100-Day GRC Challenge: Securing OpenMRS on AWS*

---

## Two Weeks In — and This One Felt Important

I have covered a lot of ground in the first two weeks. Frameworks, regulations, risk assessment, risk treatment, governance documents. Today brought a lot of that together in a way that felt genuinely clarifying. Because underneath all of those frameworks and checklists is a tension that comes up constantly in GRC — and getting it wrong has real consequences.

The tension is this: compliance and security are related, but they are not the same thing. And organizations that treat them as identical tend to end up with neither.

---

## What I Worked On Today

Compliance means meeting the requirements set by a regulation, standard, or framework. HIPAA compliance means satisfying the Security Rule's administrative, physical, and technical safeguard requirements. PCI DSS compliance means meeting the 12 core requirements for protecting cardholder data. ISO 27001 compliance means implementing a documented ISMS that meets the standard's criteria.

Meeting those requirements matters. The regulations exist for good reasons and the penalties for non-compliance are real. But compliance has an inherent limitation that is important to understand: it is a snapshot.

A compliance audit or assessment captures whether you met the requirements at a specific point in time. It does not capture what happens the day after the auditors leave. It does not account for new vulnerabilities that emerge after the assessment. It does not reflect whether the people in your organization actually understand and follow the policies that looked good on paper. It does not tell you whether your controls would hold up under a real attack rather than a structured review.

Security, by contrast, is continuous. It requires active monitoring, regular testing, ongoing staff awareness, timely patching, and the willingness to honestly reassess your posture as threats evolve. Security is never finished. Compliance has an end date. That fundamental difference is what creates the gap — and the gap is where breaches happen.

---

## What Actually Clicked for Me

The analogy that clicked for me today is fitness. You cannot get fit once and stay fit forever without ongoing effort. Passing a fitness test in January does not mean you are fit in June if you stopped exercising in February. Security works the same way. A clean compliance audit in one quarter does not mean you are secure in the next if you have stopped actively monitoring, patching, reviewing access, and testing controls in the meantime.

Compliance gives you a baseline and a checkpoint. Security is what you do between checkpoints — and after them. The organizations that understand this distinction build programs that use compliance as a foundation and then go further. The organizations that do not tend to treat the audit as the goal and get caught off guard when something goes wrong in between.

I also found myself thinking about what compliance is actually designed to do. Regulations like HIPAA are not written by people who believe that meeting the minimum standard produces genuinely secure organizations. They are written to establish a floor — a minimum level of protection below which organizations should not fall. The floor is not the ceiling. It was never meant to be.

