## The Target Breach Revisited — Through a New Lens

I covered the Target breach briefly on Day 8 when I was studying PCI DSS. Today I came back to it with a more specific focus on the compliance versus security distinction — and it landed differently.

Target was PCI DSS compliant as of September 2013. Three months later, attackers compromised their point-of-sale systems and stole the payment card data of approximately 40 million customers. The breach was one of the most damaging retail security incidents in history.

The post-breach investigations revealed several things that compliance had not caught. Monitoring systems had actually detected suspicious activity during the attack — but the alerts were not acted on in time. Third-party vendor access controls were not managed with sufficient rigor. Network segmentation that should have contained a breach was not as robust as a compliance checklist might have suggested.

What I find most instructive about this case from today's perspective is not that Target was breached — breaches happen to well-resourced organizations. It is that the compliance process did not surface the gaps that the attackers exploited. PCI DSS did not fail because it is a bad standard. It was limited by the inherent nature of compliance: it assessed what was in place at a point in time, not whether those controls would hold up under real adversarial pressure.

The question that stayed with me is: what would a genuinely security-minded organization have done differently? Probably not a fundamentally different set of controls — but a fundamentally different relationship with those controls. Treating monitoring as a real-time operational function rather than a compliance checkbox. Conducting adversarial testing to find gaps before attackers do. Reviewing third-party access with genuine scrutiny rather than paperwork. Those are security behaviors, not compliance behaviors.

