## Applying This to OpenMRS on AWS

This distinction plays out directly in how you think about securing OpenMRS. Imagine an organization that has done the following:

- Written an access control policy ✓
- Enabled encryption on the database ✓
- Conducted HIPAA staff training ✓
- Passed an internal compliance review ✓

That looks like a compliant system. But now ask the security questions:

- Are access reviews actually being conducted, or just scheduled on paper?
- Is the encryption configuration being monitored, or was it set up once and assumed to still be working?
- Did staff actually retain anything from the training, or did they click through it to get the completion certificate?
- When was the last time someone tested whether the backup could actually be restored?
- Has anyone reviewed the AWS security group rules since the system was first configured?

Each of those questions points to a place where a compliant system can drift into an insecure one — not through a dramatic failure but through gradual neglect. Policies age. Configurations drift. People come and go. Threats evolve. A system that was genuinely secure at the time of an audit can become genuinely vulnerable over the following months if no one is actively maintaining it.

