## A Real-World Example That Made This Click — Beyond Target

While researching today's topic I came across the **2015 Excellus BlueCross BlueShield breach** — a healthcare insurer that was breached in an attack that went undetected for nearly two years, ultimately exposing the data of 10 million people. Excellus was subject to HIPAA requirements and had compliance processes in place.

What the post-breach investigation found was a pattern familiar from other cases: the organization had documentation and policies, but the active security behaviors — monitoring, vulnerability management, regular access reviews — had not kept pace with the threat environment. The attackers had persistent access to the network for approximately 20 months before the breach was discovered.

Twenty months. That is a long time for an attacker to be present in a system that had passed compliance reviews. It is also a clear illustration of what the compliance-security gap looks like in practice. Compliance processes did not detect the intrusion. Active security monitoring — had it been in place and functioning — might have.

Excellus paid a $5.1 million HIPAA settlement. More importantly, 10 million people had their personal health information compromised over nearly two years. The compliance documentation did not protect them. Only active, ongoing security practices could have done that.

